T1  - Decisions Under Uncertainty as Bayesian Inference on Choice Options
AU  - Vieider, Ferdinand M.
Y1  - 2024/03/19
PY  - 2024
DA  - 2024/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2023.00265
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2023.00265
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 9014
EP  - 9030
VL  - 70
IS  - 12
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Standard models of decision making under risk and uncertainty are deterministic. Inconsistencies in choices are accommodated by separate error models. The combination of decision model and error model, however, is arbitrary. Here, I derive a model of decision making under uncertainty in which choice options are mentally encoded by noisy signals, which are optimally decoded by Bayesian combination with preexisting information. The model predicts diminishing sensitivity toward both likelihoods and rewards, thus providing cognitive microfoundations for the patterns documented in the prospect theory literature. The model is, however, inherently stochastic, so that choices and noise are determined by the same underlying parameters. This results in several novel predictions, which I test on one existing data set and in two new experiments.This paper was accepted by Manel Baucells, behavioral economics and decision analysis.Funding: The author gratefully acknowledges financial support from the Research Foundation?Flanders (FWO) under the project ?Causal Determinants of Preferences? [Grant G008021N] and the special research fund (BOF) at Ghent University under the project ?The role of noise in the determination of risk preferences.?Supplemental Material: The online appendix and data files are available at https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2023.00265.
